R 17. Are People an Environmental Pollution? -- tCHAPTER 18. Population Density Does Not Damage Health, or Psychological and Social Well- Being -- tCHAPTER 19. The Big Economic Picture: Population Growth and Living Standards in MDCs -- tCHAPTER 20. The Big Picture II.- LDCs -- tPART THREE. BEYOND THE DATA -- tCHAPTER 21. The Politics and Finances of Population Control -- tCHAPTER 22. The Rhetoric of Population Control: Does the End Justify the Means? -- tCHAPTER 23. Ultimately - What Are Your Values? -- tCONCLUSION. The Ultimate Resource -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tSource Notes for Figures -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA lively answer to those who sound alarms about population growth and resource useThe Ultimate Resource challenges conventional beliefs about the scarcity of energy and natural resources, the pollution of the environment, and the perils of overpopulation for our standard of living. In this provocative book, Julian Lincoln Simon argues that natural resources are not finite in any meaningful way, and that using such resources now will not slow the rate of future economic growth. In the short run, all resources are limited. A greater use of any resource means pressure on its supply and hence an increased price. In the long run, however, history shows that human creativity overcomes natural obstacles to economic growth and leads to a lower cost and price than before. The ultimate resource, Simon contends, is the human imagination coupled to the human spirit.This timely book will fundamentally change how you think about a host of issues, from immigration and human fertility to forecasts of population change and the use of taxpayer dollars for population control. The Ultimate Resource demonstrates that the primary constraint on our national and world economic growth is our capacity for the creation of new ideas. The more people who can be trained to help solve the problems that confront us, the faster we might remove the obstacles, and the greater the economic inheritance we can bequeath to our descendants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomic policy. 0aNatural resources. 0aPopulation. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691261201?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691261201423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691261201/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles